								üöÄÔ∏èBASIC UNIX COMMANDS
													
	üëâÔ∏èUNIX USERS COMMANDS
	
		These commands allow you to get basic information about Unix users in your environment.
		
		whoami ‚Äì show your username
		
		id ‚Äì print user identity
		
		groups ‚Äì show which groups user belongs to
		
		passwd ‚Äì change user password
		
		who ‚Äì find out who is logged into the system
		
		last ‚Äì show history of logins into the system
		
	üëâÔ∏èUNIX FILE OPERATIONS
	
		Navigating filesystem and managing files and access permissions:
		
		nslookup google.com ‚Äì server address
		
		cp ‚Äì copy files (work in progress)
		
		rm ‚Äì remove files and directories (work in progress)
		
		mv ‚Äì rename or move files and directories to another location
		
		echo ‚Äì ‚Äúhello world‚Äù
		
		chown ‚Äì change file/directory ownership
						
	üëâÔ∏èUNIX DIRECTORY MANAGEMENT COMMANDS
	
		Navigating filesystems and managing directories:
		
		cd ‚Äì change directory
		
		pwd ‚Äì confirm current directory
		
		mkdir ‚Äì make new directory
		
		rmdir ‚Äì remove directories in Unix
		
	‚òòÔ∏èCONTROL COMMANDS:
	
		üíªÔ∏è1)=>Command ps - displays a snapshot of all current processes
		
		Common Syntax		$ ps [options]
		Example 			$ ps -ef
		Show every process running, formatted as a table	
		
		
		
		üíªÔ∏è2)=>Command top - displays a live status of current processes
		
		Common Syntax		$ top [options]
		Example			$ top
		Show a live view of all current processes
		
		
		
		üíªÔ∏è3)=>Command bg - resume a background suspended a job
		
		Common Syntax		$ bg [job_spec ‚Ä¶]
		Example			$ xterm
						Ctrl-Z
						$ bg
		Continue running a job that was previously suspended (using Ctrl-Z) in the background
		
		
		
		üíªÔ∏è4)=>Command clear ‚Äì clear a terminal screen
		
		Common Syntax$ clear
		Example        		$ clear
		Clear all prior text from the terminal screen
		
		
		
		üíªÔ∏è5)=>Command history ‚Äì print history of commands in the current session
		
		Common Syntax		$ history [options]
		Example			$ history
			
			
	üìëÔ∏èBASIC ONES'		
			
			
		üñ•Ô∏è#1) touch: Create a new file or update its timestamp.
		
			‚Ä¢Syntax: touch [OPTION]‚Ä¶[FILE]
			‚Ä¢Example: Create empty files called ‚Äòfile1‚Äô and ‚Äòfile2‚Äô
			‚Ä¢$ touch file1 file2
		
		
		üñ•Ô∏è#2) cat: Concatenate files and print to stdout.
		
			‚Ä¢Syntax: cat [OPTION]‚Ä¶[FILE]
			‚Ä¢Example: Create file1 with entered cotent
			‚Ä¢$ cat > file1
			‚Ä¢Hello
		
		
		üñ•Ô∏è#3) cp: Copy files
		
			‚Ä¢Syntax: cp [OPTION]source destination
			‚Ä¢Example: Copies the contents from file1 to file2 and the contents of file1 are retained
			‚Ä¢$ cp file1 file2
		
		üñ•Ô∏è#4) mv: Move files or rename files
		
			‚Ä¢Syntax: mv [OPTION]source destination
			‚Ä¢Example: Create empty files called ‚Äòfile1‚Äô and ‚Äòfile2‚Äô
			‚Ä¢$ mv file1 file2
		
		
		üñ•Ô∏è#5) rm: Remove files and directories
		
			‚Ä¢Syntax: rm [OPTION]‚Ä¶[FILE]
			‚Ä¢Example: Delete file1
			$ rm file1
		
		
		üñ•Ô∏è#6) mkdir: Make a directory
		
			‚Ä¢Syntax: mkdir [OPTION] directory
			‚Ä¢Example: Create a directory called dir1
			‚Ä¢$ mkdir dir1
			
			
		üñ•Ô∏è#7) rmdir: Remove a directory
		
			‚Ä¢Syntax: rmdir [OPTION] directory
			‚Ä¢Example: Create empty files called ‚Äòfile1‚Äô and ‚Äòfile2‚Äô
			‚Ä¢$ rmdir dir1
			
			
		üñ•Ô∏è#8) cd: Change directory
		
			‚Ä¢Syntax: cd [OPTION] directory
			‚Ä¢Example: Change working directory to dir1
			‚Ä¢$ cd dir1
			
			
		üñ•Ô∏è#9) pwd: Print the present working directory
		
			‚Ä¢Syntax: pwd [OPTION]
			‚Ä¢Example: Print ‚Äòdir1‚Äô if a current working directory is dir1
			
			
		üñ•Ô∏è#10) ls: List directory contents
		
			‚Ä¢Syntax: ls [OPTION] [FILE]
			‚Ä¢Example: list all (including hidden files) directory contents, in long format, sorted by
			‚Ä¢$ ls -alt
			‚Ä¢
			‚Ä¢
			‚Ä¢
			$ls -l
			$ls -ltr
			$ls -a
			
			
		üñ•Ô∏è#11) which: Locate a command
		
			‚Ä¢Syntax: which [-a] filename
			‚Ä¢Example: List all paths from where ‚Äòcat‚Äô can run
			‚Ä¢$ which -a cat
			
			
		üñ•Ô∏è#12) man: Interface for working with the online reference manuals.
		
			‚Ä¢Syntax: man [-s section] item
			‚Ä¢Example: Show the manual page for the ‚Äòcat‚Äô command
			‚Ä¢$ man cat
			
			
		üñ•Ô∏è#13) su: Change user-id or become super-user.
		
			‚Ä¢Syntax: su [options] [username]
			‚Ä¢Example: Change user-id to ‚Äòuser1‚Äô (if it exists)
			‚Ä¢$ su user1
			
			
		üñ•Ô∏è#14) sudo: Execute a command as some other user or super-user
		
			‚Ä¢Syntax: sudo [options] [command]
			‚Ä¢Example: Get a file listing of an unlisted directory
			‚Ä¢$ sudo ls /usr/local/protected
			
			
		üñ•Ô∏è#15) find: Used to search for files and directories as mentioned in the ‚Äòexpression‚Äô
		
			‚Ä¢Syntax: find [starting-point] [expression]
			‚Ä¢Example: In ‚Äò/usr‚Äô folder, find character device files, of the name ‚Äòbackup‚Äô
			‚Ä¢$ find /usr -type c -name backup
			
			
		üñ•Ô∏è#16) du: Estimate disk usage is blocks
		
			‚Ä¢Syntax: du [options] [file]
			‚Ä¢Example: Show the number of blocks occupied by files in the current directory
			‚Ä¢$ du
		
		
		üñ•Ô∏è#17) df: Show the number of free blocks for the mounted file system
		
			‚Ä¢Syntax: df [options] [file]
			‚Ä¢Example: Show the number of free blocks in local file systems
			‚Ä¢$ df -l
			
		
		üñ•Ô∏è#18) cal: Displays the calendar.
		
			‚Ä¢Syntax: cal [[month] year]
			‚Ä¢Example: display the calendar for April 2018
			‚Ä¢$ cal 4 2018
		
		
		üñ•Ô∏è#19) date: Displays the system date and time.
		
			‚Ä¢Syntax: date [+format]
			‚Ä¢Example: Display the date in dd/mm/yy format
			‚Ä¢$ date +%d/%m/%y
			
			
		üñ•Ô∏è#20) who: Displays the list of users currently logged in
		
			Syntax: who [option] ‚Ä¶ [file][arg1]
			6|Page‚Ä¢Example: List all currently logged-in users
			‚Ä¢$ who
			
			
		üñ•Ô∏è#21) whoami: Displays the user id of the currently logged-in user.
		
			‚Ä¢Syntax: whoami [option]
			‚Ä¢Example: List currently logged-in user
			‚Ä¢$ whoami
			
	
	üìëÔ∏èSOME MORE IMPORTANT COMMANDS
	
			üîñÔ∏èGrep command in Unix:
	
			     The grep command in Unix/Linux is a powerful tool used for searching and manipulating text patterns within files.
			     In this article, we will explore the various aspects of the grep command.
			     
				-c: This prints only a count of the lines that match a pattern
				-h: Display the matched lines, but do not display the filenames.
				-l: Displays list of a filenames only.
				-n: Display the matched lines and their line numbers.
				-v: This prints out all the lines that do not matches the pattern
				-e : Specifies expression with this option. Can use multiple times.
				-o :Print only the matched parts of a matching line, with each such part on a separate output line.
			     
			     Example:	grep -o "unix" geekfile.txt
			     			grep "^unix" geekfile.txt
			     			grep -v "unix" geekfile.txt
			     			
			     			
			 üîñÔ∏èSed Command in Unix:
			 
			      SED is a powerful text stream editor. Can do insertion, deletion,search and replace(substitution).
			      
			      Example:       Consider the below text file as an input.
					         $cat > geekfile.txt
			     
			     Replacing or substituting string : Sed command is mostly used to replace the text in a file.
			     
			     $sed 's/unix/linux/' geekfile.txt
			     
			     
			üîñÔ∏èSort Command:
			
			      In Unix-based operating systems, the sort command is used to sort the lines of a text file or input stream.
			     
			     Syntax : sort file.txt
			     
			     	-o: Specifies an output file for the sorted data.Functionally equivalent to redirecting output to a file.
				-r: Sorts data in reverse order (descending).
				-n: Sorts a file numerically (interprets data as numbers).
				-nr: Sorts a file with numeric data in reverse order.Combines -n and -r options.
				-k: Sorts a table based on a specific column number.
				-c: Checks if the file is already sorted and reports any disorder.
			     	-u: Sorts and removes duplicate lines, providing a unique sorted list.
				-M: Sorts by month names.
			     
			üîñÔ∏èchmod Command:
			
			      In Unix operating systems, the chmod command is used to change the access mode of a file.
			     
			     Operators			Definition:
				
				`+`				Add permissions
				`-`				Remove permissions
				`=`				Set the permissions to the specified values
			     
			üîñÔ∏èAWK command in Unix:
			
			    Awk is a powerful text processing tool available in Unix and Unix-like operating systems. It is particularly useful for processing structured text files.
			     
			    Example:	Consider the following text file as the input file for all cases below:
						$cat > employee.txt
						ajay manager account 45000
						sunil clerk account 25000
						varun manager sales 50000
			     
			     			Print the lines which match the given pattern.
			     
						$ awk '/manager/ {print}' employee.txt
			     
			     
			üîñÔ∏èshutdown command:
			
			    The shutdown command in Linux is used to shutdown the system in a safe way.
			     
			    Syntax : shutdown [options] [time] [message]
			    
				         shutdown -r +5 reboot
				         
				        options ‚Äì Shutdown options such as halt, power-off (the default option) or reboot the system.
				        time ‚Äì The time argument specifies when to perform the shutdown process.
				        message ‚Äì The message argument specifies a message which will be broadcast to all users.
			     
			     
			     
			
												     
